<title> Duration token </title>

<h1> Duration token </h1>

<subsection>

<p> Abjad notes, rests, chords, tuplets and other durated components accept duration input in a couple of different formats.

<ul>
   <li> Abjad <Rational> instances
   <li> Python pairs
   <li> Python <tt>int</tt> and <tt>long</tt> instances
</ul>

<p> For example:

<abjad>
   abjad> note = Note(0, Rational(1, 4))
   hide> measure = Measure((1, 4), [note])
   hide> measure.meter.transparent = True
   hide> staff = RhythmicStaff([measure])
   hide> show(staff)
</abjad>

<p> And:

<abjad>
   abjad> note = Note(0, (3, 8))
   hide> measure = Measure((3, 8), [note])
   hide> measure.meter.transparent = True
   hide> staff = RhythmicStaff([measure])
   hide> show(staff)
</abjad>

<p> And:

<abjad>
   abjad> note = Note(0, 1)
   hide> measure = Measure((1, 1), [note])
   hide> measure.meter.transparent = True
   hide> staff = RhythmicStaff([measure])
   hide> show(staff)
</abjad>

<p> The Abjad <strong>duration token</strong> generalizes these different types of input.

<p> Examples in the documentation that ask for valid duration token input accept any of the types of input show here.

</subsection>

<comments>

<p> Abjad does not count the Python <tt>float</tt> among the valid types of duration token.

</comments>
